Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - SI prefix table
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Each prefix is a 6-bit identifier (so a Quantity could pack the
Note: prefix into the unit-tag itself for very compact storage in a
Note: future extension). For now we expose them as scale-multiplier
Note: lookup functions.

Process called "prefix_id_yocto" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_zepto" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_atto" returns Integer:
    Return 3
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_femto" returns Integer:
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_pico" returns Integer:
    Return 5
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_nano" returns Integer:
    Return 6
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_micro" returns Integer:
    Return 7
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_milli" returns Integer:
    Return 8
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_centi" returns Integer:
    Return 9
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_deci" returns Integer:
    Return 10
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_deca" returns Integer:
    Return 11
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_hecto" returns Integer:
    Return 12
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_kilo" returns Integer:
    Return 13
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_mega" returns Integer:
    Return 14
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_giga" returns Integer:
    Return 15
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_tera" returns Integer:
    Return 16
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_peta" returns Integer:
    Return 17
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_exa" returns Integer:
    Return 18
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_zetta" returns Integer:
    Return 19
End Process

Process called "prefix_id_yotta" returns Integer:
    Return 20
End Process

Process called "unit_prefix_scale" takes prefix as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the Float64 multiplier for one of the standard SI prefixes.
        Used by unit_parse when a textual specifier like "km" is split
        into prefix "k" and base unit "m".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Hard-coded branch ladder of the 20 standard SI prefixes from
        yocto (10^-24) through yotta (10^24).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 20 cycles worst case.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Unknown prefix returns 1.0 (no scaling).
    @End Security_Scope
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_yocto) :
        Return 1.0 divided by 1.0e24
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_zepto) :
        Return 1.0 divided by 1.0e21
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_atto) :
        Return 1.0 divided by 1.0e18
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_femto) :
        Return 1.0 divided by 1.0e15
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_pico) :
        Return 1.0 divided by 1.0e12
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_nano) :
        Return 1.0 divided by 1.0e9
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_micro) :
        Return 1.0 divided by 1.0e6
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_milli) :
        Return 0.001
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_centi) :
        Return 0.01
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_deci) :
        Return 0.1
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_deca) :
        Return 1.0e1
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_hecto) :
        Return 1.0e2
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_kilo) :
        Return 1.0e3
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_mega) :
        Return 1.0e6
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_giga) :
        Return 1.0e9
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_tera) :
        Return 1.0e12
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_peta) :
        Return 1.0e15
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_exa) :
        Return 1.0e18
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_zetta) :
        Return 1.0e21
    End If
    If prefix is equal to (proc prefix_id_yotta) :
        Return 1.0e24
    End If
    Return 1.0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Unit composition and pow
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "unit_compose_op_mul" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "unit_compose_op_div" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "unit_compose" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, op as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Combine two unit tags into a resulting tag for the multiplication
        or division of the underlying quantities. When the result matches
        a named SI derived unit (e.g. m * kg / s^2 -> N) we return that
        named tag; otherwise we return COMPOSITE_TAG.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute the resulting dimension via dim_mul / dim_div on the
        operand dimensions, then test against the canonical derived
        dimensions. The product-of-base-units composition (any pair of
        base units that does not equal a named derived dimension)
        returns COMPOSITE_TAG so the Quantity's dimension field carries
        the truth and the tag is purely cosmetic.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two dimension lookups, one algebraic step, ~ 5 compare steps
        for the named-derived-unit recognizer. ~ 80 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let da be proc unit_get_dimension with a
    Let db be proc unit_get_dimension with b
    Let dr be 0
    If op is equal to (proc unit_compose_op_mul) :
        Set dr to proc dim_mul from Dim with da, db
    Otherwise:
        Set dr to proc dim_div from Dim with da, db
    End If
    Note: Recognize common derived dimensions
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with dr, (proc dim_create from Dim with 1, 1, 0 minus 2, 0, 0, 0, 0)) is equal to 1:
        Return proc unit_tag_newton
    End If
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with dr, (proc dim_create from Dim with 2, 1, 0 minus 2, 0, 0, 0, 0)) is equal to 1:
        Return proc unit_tag_joule
    End If
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with dr, (proc dim_create from Dim with 2, 1, 0 minus 3, 0, 0, 0, 0)) is equal to 1:
        Return proc unit_tag_watt
    End If
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with dr, (proc dim_create from Dim with 0 minus 1, 1, 0 minus 2, 0, 0, 0, 0)) is equal to 1:
        Return proc unit_tag_pascal
    End If
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with dr, (proc dim_create from Dim with 0, 0, 0 minus 1, 0, 0, 0, 0)) is equal to 1:
        Return proc unit_tag_hertz
    End If
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with dr, (proc dim_create from Dim with 0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0)) is equal to 1:
        Return proc unit_tag_coulomb
    End If
    Return proc unit_tag_composite
End Process

Process called "unit_pow" takes tag as Integer, exponent as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Raise a unit tag to an integer power. Currently we return
        COMPOSITE_TAG for all non-trivial powers because the named-derived
        recognition path is only valid for the named composites above;
        m^2, m^3, m^-1 etc. carry meaningful dimensions but no dedicated
        symbol so the Quantity dimension field already captures the truth.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        If exponent is 0 the result is dimensionless and we return the
        unknown tag (with dimensionless dimension). If exponent is 1 we
        return the input tag. Otherwise COMPOSITE_TAG.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If exponent is equal to 0:
        Return proc unit_tag_unknown
    End If
    If exponent is equal to 1:
        Return tag
    End If
    Return proc unit_tag_composite
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - String parser
Note: ============================================================================
Note: A lightweight parser for canonical unit symbols. Recognises the
Note: short symbol strings in the registry above and the cumulative SI
Note: prefix. The pair (tag, scale_extra) is returned via two-call
Note: convention because stage1 has no tuple return.

Process called "unit_parse_tag_from_symbol" takes symbol as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Match a textual short symbol against the registry. Returns the
        unit tag, or unit_tag_unknown if no match. Note that prefixes
        are NOT handled here - callers wanting full "km" -> (METER, 1000)
        should use unit_parse below.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Hard-coded match against the canonical symbol strings. The
        bootstrap stdlib has no general-purpose hash table for short
        strings; the registry has ~ 50 entries so the linear scan is
        adequate.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Worst case ~ 50 string-equality calls. ~ 500 cycles for the
        full sweep.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 200:
        Let candidate_symbol be proc unit_get_symbol with i
        Let match be proc string_equals_runa with candidate_symbol, symbol
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return i
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return proc unit_tag_unknown
End Process

Process called "string_equals_runa" takes a as String, b as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Compare two Runa strings byte-by-byte. Used by unit_parse_tag_from_symbol
        for the short-symbol match. Delegates to StrCore.string_equals which
        already implements the production-grade comparison loop.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Forward call to StrCore.string_equals returning the same 0/1 result.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        O(min(|a|, |b|)).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc string_equals from StrCore with a, b
End Process
